\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 11. P. sibiricus} (J. F. Gmelin) Dingwall,{\i  Bot. Jour. Linn. Soc.}{\b  71}: 273 (1975) ({\i P. gmelinii} Polunin,{\i  Tussilago sibirica} J. F. Gmelin). Leaves elliptical to ovate, cuneate to truncate at the base, without a sinus; margin weakly and remotely toothed. Scapes with 3-4 scale-leaves, the lower sheathing the stem at the base, the middle 1·3-2 cm, none with a rudimentary lamina. Capitula 1-3; involucre 6-7 mm; bracts purplish, sparsely tomentose, with an entire to somewhat ciliate apex. Florets whitish. Ligules in the female c. 3·5 mm.{\i  Stony tundra. N. Ural.} Rs (N). ({\i N. Asia and North America}.)
